	<h3>Introduction</h3>
	<p>
		My title is Product Architect, also known as Solution Architect or Application Architect / Technology Leader. 
		My mission is to transition engineering culture from "Master Blacksmiths" (manual, effort-based labor) 
		to "Master Goldsmiths" (high-precision logic, handling business uncertainty).
	</p>
	<p>
		My AI philosophy is that AI is the "Great Teacher" and the engine for structural "90%" tasks, 
		with human value found in the final "10%" of refinement and business alignment. I wear multiple hats: 
		reviewing existing service architecture and planning migration, designing architecture for new features 
		in legacy products, creating architecture for greenfield products, and refining the target state reference architecture.
	</p>

	<p>
		My strengths are my vulnerability about not being an expert and my adaptability to learn what I don't know or can't do. 
		My weaknesses are over discussion, able to learn less verbally and more visually, and not being disciplined.
	</p>

	<p>
		My values are clarity, maintainability, and consistency in architecture. I emphasize test coverage, CI/CD readiness, 
		and responsive design. I advocate for internal package reuse via NuGet and npm feeds. I use standard project templates 
		and scripts for front-end and modernization efforts. I apply strict linting and formatting standards across projects.
	</p>

	<h3>Architectural Principles (The "Lego" Framework)</h3>
	
	<h4>Standardized Skeleton</h4>
	<p>Foundations must be rigid and follow company-proven patterns (.NET, REST, SQL, established NuGet/npm feeds). Modular Joints: Use Spec-Driven Development (SDD) to define immutable interfaces.</p>

	<h4>Lego Slices</h4>
	<p>Features should be built as independent Lego pieces. As long as they fit the standardized "joints" (contracts), they can be developed in parallel without falling into the Waterfall trap.</p>

	<h4>Repairable Anatomy</h4>
	<p>Design for "plastic surgery." Components should be modular enough to be repaired or replaced without compromising the core skeleton.</p>

	<h4>Tech Stack</h4>
	<p>
		At my workplace, the current tech stack includes .NET (C# 10), React with TypeScript and Vite, MSSQL, MongoDB, 
		legacy WinForms/.NET Framework desktop apps in C#, legacy Angular apps, REST APIs, Terraform, Docker, Kubernetes 
		(On-Prem with Rancher and ArgoCD), On-Prem VMs, Azure offerings, Azure DevOps Repos with GitHub backend, Azure DevOps for CI/CD, 
		ServiceNow, Open Telemetry (Elastic and DataDog), Microsoft Azure, Python, Databricks (serverless on Azure), Azure Data Fabric, 
		Informatica, BI, Kafka (Confluent Cloud), Elasticsearch, Oracle ERP, Transportation Management SaaS, and Boomi (On-Prem). 
		For integration, I also use Fivetran HVR for CDC and Azure API Management.
	</p>
	<p>
		My past experience includes Java Springboot, Apigee, MuleSoft, GCP, AWS, PeopleSoft, Red Hat Linux, and Oracle Exadata. 
		I have followed the trajectory of Software Development Engineer to Technical Lead to Solutions Architect role 
		with brief stints as Business Analyst, Delivery Lead and Integration Architect.
	</p>

	<ul>
		<li>I prioritize diagrams, structured lists, and technical clarity over dense prose.</li>
		<li>I prefer Hexagonal (Port and Adapter) architecture for complex domain APIs, often aided by CQRS and DDD, but values simplicity over complexity.</li>
		<li>I appreciate the SOLID principles and also the counter-principles of CUPID. I have extensive experience with MACH and PBC architectures and is an expert in COTS applications.</li>
		<li>I have a well-defined ideal architecture combining GraphQL for UI-facing APIs, gRPC with Protobuf for internal service communication, Kafka for asynchronous messaging, and REST for external integrations.</li>
		<li>I prefer a hybrid microservices system using DDD, CQRS, and Ports & Adapters architecture, and values design-first/spec-first approaches with strong schema management and observability tooling.</li>
		<li>I adapt this ideal architecture pragmatically within enterprise constraints.</li>
	</ul>

